## Canonical SKILL.md Format

The YAML frontmatter has two required keys. Do NOT emit `tags`, `allowed_tools`, `category`, `version`, or any other field.

- `name` — kebab-case identifier. Max 64 chars. Lowercase letters, digits, hyphens only. Must not contain `anthropic` or `claude`.
- `description` — one paragraph written in the third person that states BOTH what the skill does AND the concrete triggers (user phrases, task types) that should invoke it. Start with a verb phrase. Example: "Run test suites, diagnose failures, and propose fixes. This skill should be used when users ask to fix failing tests, investigate CI errors, or rerun a flaky spec."

## Body Style

- Write in imperative/infinitive form ("To rotate a PDF, run ...", not "You should rotate ...").
- Explain WHY, not just WHAT. Today's models respond better to reasoning than all-caps imperatives.
- Use headings, ordered steps, and bullets. Prefer bullets over prose.
- Include a section on what the skill should NOT do (negative cases).
- Keep the body lean — procedural instructions only. Offload schemas, templates, long reference tables to `references/` in your prose (even though we do not generate bundled resources here, mention them when they'd be useful).
- To hit the required length budget, include ALL of these sections at minimum: a one-paragraph overview, **When to Invoke** (with at least 4 concrete trigger phrases or signals), **Core Workflow** (at least 5 numbered steps, each with a rationale sentence), **Worked Example** (a realistic before/after scenario grounded in the evidence), **When NOT to Use This Skill** (at least 3 negative cases), and **Tools**. Bodies shorter than 1,200 words almost always omit the Worked Example or give a sparse Core Workflow — expand those first.

## Progressive Disclosure

Skills load in layers: the name+description are always in context; the SKILL.md body loads when the skill triggers; bundled resources (scripts/, references/, assets/) load only on demand. Keep the body lean so Claude can page in only what matters.

## Your Task

Generate a complete, production-ready SKILL.md for the given proposal. Ground every step in the session evidence provided.

## Example SKILL.md

```markdown
---
name: test-fix-loop
description: Run failing tests, read the failure output, locate the broken code, and propose a minimal fix. This skill should be used when users ask to "fix tests", "diagnose a CI failure", "rerun a flaky test", or when test output shows assertion errors, stack traces, or missing fixtures.
---

[Body]
```

## Output Rules

- Return ONLY valid JSON matching the schema. No ``` fences around the JSON object itself (the ``` inside `skill_md_content` is fine — escape normally).
- The YAML frontmatter inside `skill_md_content` must contain ONLY `name` and `description`.
- `description` field in the JSON must mirror the frontmatter `description` (third person, what + when).
- `tools_used` (top-level JSON field) lists the tool names referenced by the skill — do NOT add it to the YAML frontmatter.
- NEVER reference sessions by ID, index, or UUID in text fields. Describe patterns in general terms.
- All text fields must be plain language, understandable by non-technical users.

